    <li><strong>Real-world treatment continuity:</strong> 19.6% restarted original GLP-1; 35.2% received alternative obesity treatment within 1 year</li>
    <li><strong>Outcome heterogeneity:</strong> 45% of obesity discontinuers maintained or continued losing weight; 55% gained</li>
    <li><strong>BMJ Meta-Analysis (37 studies, 9,000+ adults):</strong> ~0.4 kg/month regain rate — 4× faster than after behavioral programs alone</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="mechanism" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Biology Has Not Been Negotiated Away</h2>
  <p>None of the real-world data changes what happens inside the body when GLP-1 receptor stimulation ends. That story is worth telling precisely, because "your hunger comes back" is a grotesque undersimplification of a coordinated physiological counter-offensive.</p>
  <p>GLP-1 receptor agonists work through a distributed network of receptor sites: the pancreas, where they stimulate glucose-dependent insulin secretion and suppress glucagon; the hypothalamus and brainstem, where they suppress appetite and modulate reward circuitry; and the vagus nerve, where they delay gastric emptying and amplify satiety signaling. The pharmacological effect is not a single lever — it is simultaneous pressure on multiple systems that regulate energy intake and expenditure.</p>
  <p>When that pressure is removed, the body does not return passively to its prior state. It rebounds. Adipose tissue loss during treatment has already driven down circulating leptin, the hormone that signals energy sufficiency to the hypothalamus. As weight is regained, leptin rises again — but the hypothalamus, having adapted to lower leptin levels during the loss phase, requires more of it to register satiety. Simultaneously, ghrelin — the orexigenic hormone produced primarily in the stomach — rises sharply after GLP-1 withdrawal, driving hunger signals that are neurologically difficult to override through willpower alone. Resting metabolic rate, which decreases during weight loss through a process called metabolic adaptation or adaptive thermogenesis, does not recover quickly. The body is burning fewer calories at rest than it did at the same weight before treatment began. Gastric emptying, slowed by GLP-1 receptor stimulation, accelerates back toward baseline as antral motility is restored, reducing the mechanical satiety that delayed gastric emptying provides.</p>
  <p>The net result, as Dr. Susan Wolver of MedCentral has described it, is "increased hunger, a reduced resting metabolic rate, and lower total energy expenditure" converging simultaneously. This is not a character flaw. It is a homeostatic defense mechanism that evolution spent millions of years optimizing. The greater the initial weight loss — and GLP-1 agonists produce some of the largest pharmacologically induced losses ever recorded — the more aggressive the counter-response upon cessation. The biology is not impressed by the real-world data.</p>
  <p>Erica Spatz, MD, of Yale University School of Medicine, has raised the one genuinely open question that could eventually complicate this picture: whether long-term GLP-1 use might durably rewire the body's metabolic set point — not just suppress hunger pharmacologically, but alter the hormonal architecture of appetite regulation in ways that persist after the drug is gone. "Is that sufficient to say that, hormonally, these incretin hormones have changed and that our brains are no longer getting those messages that we're hungry?" Spatz asked. "I think that's an open question." It is. And we do not have the long-duration discontinuation data to answer it.</p>
</section>

<section id="cardiometabolic" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Rebound Nobody Mentions at the Scale</h2>
  <p>Weight is the metric that dominates GLP-1 discontinuation coverage. It should not be the only one.</p>
  <p>The 2025 <em>eClinicalMedicine</em> meta-analysis — 18 RCTs, 3,771 participants — found that stopping GLP-1 receptor agonists produced statistically significant deterioration across the full cardiometabolic panel: HbA1c rose, systolic blood pressure increased, waist circumference expanded, fasting plasma glucose climbed, and lipid profiles worsened. These are not surrogate markers. They are the biological substrates of cardiovascular events, stroke, and end-organ damage. The SEMAGLUTIDE and Cardiovascular Outcomes (SELECT) trial demonstrated that semaglutide reduces major adverse cardiovascular events in people with obesity and established cardiovascular disease — which means the reversal of those benefits upon discontinuation carries real downstream risk that a bathroom scale cannot capture.</p>
  <p>The Cleveland Clinic study, for all its value, does not report cardiometabolic outcomes. It measures weight. The real-world muting of the weight rebound — driven by treatment continuity — does not extend automatically to the metabolic rebound, because the metabolic rebound is a direct pharmacological consequence of GLP-1 withdrawal, not a function of whether the patient subsequently joins a lifestyle program. HbA1c does not care that your dietitian is excellent.</p>
  <p>This is the part of the discontinuation story that does not get softened by real-world treatment flexibility, and it deserves more clinical attention than it currently receives.</p>
</section>

