<section id="chronic-disease-tension" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Chronic-Disease Framing: Biologically Sound, Commercially Convenient</h2>
  <p>The argument that GLP-1 receptor agonists should be treated like antihypertensives — taken indefinitely, because the condition they treat is chronic — is biologically coherent. Obesity is a chronic, relapsing condition with a strong neurobiological substrate. Stopping an antihypertensive causes blood pressure to rise. Stopping a GLP-1 agonist causes weight to rise and metabolic markers to deteriorate. The analogy holds.</p>
  <p>It also happens to be the most commercially optimal framing available to manufacturers of drugs that cost, depending on coverage, between $900 and $1,400 per month in the United States. Novo Nordisk and Eli Lilly are not wrong that chronic-disease framing is medically defensible. They are also not disinterested parties in whether that framing prevails. Both facts are true simultaneously, and the alignment between biological accuracy and commercial interest deserves naming — not as a conspiracy, but as a structural reality that should inform how aggressively the "lifelong medication" narrative is promoted relative to the evidence for alternatives.</p>
  <p>Qi Sun, MD, of Harvard Medical School and Brigham and Women's Hospital, wrote in a <em>BMJ</em> editorial that GLP-1 receptor agonists "should not be relied on as a magic cure for treating obesity" and that "healthy dietary and lifestyle practices should remain the foundation for obesity treatment and management, with medications such as GLP-1s used as adjuncts." Adam Collins, PhD, of the University of Surrey, has noted that weight regain is "amplified" for patients who relied on the drug to do the heavy lifting during weight loss rather than building behavioral infrastructure alongside it. These are not fringe positions. They are the mainstream of evidence-based obesity medicine — and they sit in productive tension with the chronic-disease framing without invalidating it.</p>
  <p>The honest answer is that both framings are partially correct, that the evidence does not yet resolve the tension cleanly, and that the financial stakes of the resolution are enormous.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The alignment between biological accuracy and commercial interest deserves naming — not as a conspiracy, but as a structural reality that should inform how aggressively the 'lifelong medication' narrative is promoted."</p></aside>

<section id="limitations" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Cleveland Clinic Study Cannot Tell You</h2>
  <p>The Gasoyan cohort is valuable. It is not definitive, and saying so is not a caveat to be buried — it is a condition of reading the data honestly.</p>
  <p>The study is retrospective and observational, built on electronic health records and pharmacy dispensation data. It cannot establish causation. Patients who successfully transitioned to alternative treatments are almost certainly not representative of the full population stopping GLP-1s — they are, by definition, patients who remained engaged with a healthcare system capable of providing alternatives. The study drew exclusively from a single large health system in Ohio and Florida, which limits generalizability to populations with different insurance structures, access patterns, and demographic profiles. It captured only patients who stopped within three to twelve months of initiating treatment, potentially excluding longer-term users who may face different rebound dynamics after years of pharmacological appetite suppression. And it does not report cardiometabolic outcomes — the dimension of discontinuation risk that the trial literature flags most urgently.</p>
  <p>The BMJ meta-analysis carries its own caveat: its long-term projections of return to baseline weight within 1.5 to 2 years are modeled extrapolations, not directly observed outcomes. Marie Spreckley of the University of Cambridge cautioned that these projections should be interpreted carefully. Modeling is not measurement.</p>
  <p>The Gasoyan data and the BMJ meta-analysis are not in equal tension with each other. They are measuring different things: one measures what happens when real patients stop and navigate a real healthcare system; the other measures the pharmacological rebound in controlled conditions and projects it forward. Neither is wrong. Neither is complete. Treating them as contradictory findings is a category error — they are complementary datasets with different blind spots.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">GLP-1 Discontinuation: What We Know and What We Don't</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Established:</strong> Stopping GLP-1 agonists triggers a coordinated homeostatic counter-response — rising ghrelin, falling leptin sensitivity, reduced resting metabolic rate, accelerated gastric emptying</li>
    <li><strong>Established:</strong> Cardiometabolic markers (HbA1c, blood pressure, lipids, fasting glucose) deteriorate significantly after discontinuation in RCT data</li>
    <li><strong>Established:</strong> Real-world discontinuation rates range from 37% to 81% depending on population; roughly half of all GLP-1 users stop within one year</li>
    <li><strong>Established:</strong> Lower income is associated with higher discontinuation rates among diabetes patients (JAMA Network Open, 125,474-patient cohort)</li>
    <li><strong>Contested:</strong> Whether real-world weight outcomes after stopping are meaningfully better than trial data suggests — or whether the apparent improvement reflects continued treatment under a different label</li>
    <li><strong>Unknown:</strong> Whether long-term GLP-1 use can durably rewire metabolic set point such that benefits persist after discontinuation (Spatz, Yale)</li>
    <li><strong>Unknown:</strong> Optimal sequencing and tapering strategies for patients who must stop — evidence-based protocols do not yet exist</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="structural-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Safety Net Is Not Evenly Distributed</h2>
  <p>About half of all people with obesity stop using GLP-1 drugs within a year of starting. Real-world discontinuation rates, depending on population and data source, range from 37% to 81%. In the JAMA Network Open cohort of 125,474 patients, 46.5% of those with type 2 diabetes and 64.8% of those without had discontinued within one year. These are not small numbers. They represent the dominant clinical reality of GLP-1 therapy in the United States.</p>
  <p>The most common reasons patients stop, in the Cleveland Clinic cohort and elsewhere, are cost or insurance coverage limitations and side effects — not lack of efficacy. These are patients who wanted the treatment to work, who were often still motivated to manage their weight, and who were forced off the medication by structural barriers rather than biological failure. They are also, by definition, the patients least likely to have robust access to the alternative treatments that explain the muted rebound in the Gasoyan data.</p>
  <p>The JAMA Network Open study found that lower income was specifically associated with higher discontinuation rates among diabetes patients. This is the closing image the data provides, and it is not a comfortable one. The patients most likely to stop GLP-1 therapy are the patients least likely to restart it, least likely to access alternative pharmacotherapy, least likely to have insurance coverage for dietitian visits or structured lifestyle programs, and most likely to experience the full biological rebound that the trial literature documents. The 45% who maintained their weight after stopping — the finding that generated the most optimistic headlines — are disproportionately not these patients.</p>
  <p>The real-world data does not tell us that stopping is safe. It tells us that what happens after stopping matters enormously, and that our healthcare system's capacity to provide that continuity is uneven, expensive, and heavily correlated with income. The biology of weight regain is identical across ZIP codes. The safety net is not. And the gap between the trial catastrophe and the real-world muted rebound — the gap that is the whole story — closes fastest for the patients who can least afford to fall through it.</p>
</section>

